threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects a suspicious ELF binary with UPX compression
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This sample is a variant of the Mozi P2P botnet, specifically targeting MIPS-based Linux IoT devices and routers. It demonstrates extensive malicious functionality including persistence through the modification of '/etc/rc.local' and the creation of '/etc/init.d/S95baby.sh'. The binary interacts with system watchdogs (e.g., '/dev/watchdog') to prevent reboots, modifies 'iptables' to allow its own traffic, and actively scans the system to kill competing processes. It includes exploit payloads for various network vulnerabilities, specifically targeting UPnP and HNAP on devices from manufacturers like Huawei and Netgear. Concrete IOCs include Mozi-specific filenames ('Mozi.m', 'Mozi.a'), targeting of the Huawei configuration file '/mnt/jffs2/hw_ctree.xml', and network requests to 'ipinfo.io/ip' for external IP discovery.
